</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/us-army-panama-security-training-range-procedures.png" alt="A US Army soldier explains range procedures to Panamanian security forces" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>A US Army soldier explains range procedures to Panamanian security forces. Credits: Staff Sgt. Osvaldo Equite / DVIDS</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Trump‚Äôs push for increased American influence over the Panama Canal just got a major concession. A joint agreement between top security officials of Panama and the US permits America to deploy troops to Panama-controlled facilities for training, exercises, and ‚Äúother activities.‚Äù However, it falls short of allowing a permanent US base.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Critics in Panama have called the move a betrayal of national sovereignty. This issue recalls the US occupation and the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-14-04-2025-h1-1-1984-invasion" target="_blank">1989 invasion</a>, which saw the US overthrow dictator Manuel Noriega. Opposition leaders called it a ‚Äúcamouflaged invasion,‚Äù pointing to the canal‚Äôs neutrality treaty, which allows all nations to use it.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Previously, Trump expressed concerns over <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-14-04-2025-h1-2-chinas-influence-over-the-canal" target="_blank">China‚Äôs influence over the canal</a> as the Hong Kong-based CK Hutchison controlled either end. Amid rising tensions, the company announced it will offload the ports to the US asset manager BlackRock for $19B. Meanwhile, China has announced an antitrust review over the port trade.</p>
        </mj-text>
