          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
            <strong>üá∑üá∏ Serbian president launched a movement to counter student demonstrations</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
           Serbian President Aleksandar Vucic called for a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-14-04-2025-br1-9-counter-rally-in-belgrade" target="_blank">counter-rally in Belgrade</a> that brought about 55,000 supporters. In his speech at the rally, Vucic denounced the student protests as foreign-backed attempts to destabilize Serbia. He also pointed fingers at the ‚Äúarrogant political officials‚Äù who refused to speak to the people.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The event was attended by supporters like Bosnian Serb leader Milorad Dodik, who is wanted by the Bosnian authorities, and Hungarian PM Viktor Orban. Supporters expressed hope that the movement would bring national unity. Meanwhile, the student-led protest continues, and a cycling group is en route to the EU Parliament in Strasbourg to raise <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-14-04-2025-br1-10-awareness-of-corruption" target="_blank">awareness of corruption</a> in Serbia.</p>
