          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
            <strong>üá¨üá¶ Incumbent junta leader triumphed in the presidential election</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">In Gabon‚Äôs first election since the 2023 coup, incumbent military leader Gen. Brice Oligui Nguema <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-14-04-2025-br2-11-secured-the-presidential-election" target="_blank">secured the presidential election</a> with over 90% of the vote. Voting concluded on Saturday, with over 87% turnout among 920,000 eligible voters. Critics argued that the Constitution and electoral code favored Oligui Nguema.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">His main rival, former PM Alain Claude Bilie-By-Nze, warned of potential electoral fraud and cast doubt on the vote‚Äôs transparency. Some election observers reported being denied permission to enter the polling stations. This election was critical for the resource-rich nation, which is grappling with <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-14-04-2025-br2-12-economic-challenges" target="_blank">economic challenges</a>. It can also serve as a test case for democratic transitions in the Sahel region. </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
