          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Is Bhutan‚Äôs ‚Äúkingdom of happiness‚Äù really happy?
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/bhutanese-women-traditional-attire-cultural-heritage-kira-toego.png" alt="Dressed in traditional kira and toego, Bhutanese women embody the vibrant heritage of a country where cultural preservation meets modern challenges" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>Dressed in traditional kira and toego, Bhutanese women embody the vibrant heritage of a country where cultural preservation meets modern challenges. Credits: Borgen Project</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Bhutan proclaims itself the happiest nation in the world. However, by most global measurements of ‚Äúhappiness,‚Äù it is surpassed by dozens of other countries. According to the World Happiness Report (WHR), Finland consistently ranks as the happiest country. The WHR, however, has been criticized for primarily focusing on economic indicators, often equating higher earnings with greater happiness.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          The <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-14-04-2025-f1-13-world-hapiness-report-2025" target="_blank">World Happiness Report 2025</a> ranked Bhutan 97th in overall happiness. This tiny country in the Himalayas has multiple reasons for being ranked so low. </p>
        <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">‚Üí</span><strong>Unemployment:</strong> The tourism-based economy didn‚Äôt fully recover from the effects of the pandemic. One in eight Bhutanese live in poverty, with youth unemployment at 28.6% in 2022. This is taking a toll on them.</p>
        <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">‚Üí</span><strong>Press freedom:</strong> According to the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-14-04-2025-f1-14-2023-world-press-freedom-index" target="_blank">2023 World Press Freedom Index</a>, Bhutan ranks 90th in press freedom.</p>
        <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">‚Üí</span><strong>Political choices:</strong> Almost 20% of the 2022 Gross National Happiness survey participants said they had no right to join the political party of their choice.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">In response, Bhutan introduced its own measure: <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-14-04-2025-f1-15-gross-national-happiness" target="_blank">Gross National Happiness (GNH)</a>, a holistic index prioritizing well-being over purely economic measures like GDP, and ranked itself first.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">However, some view this as a veneer for deeper issues within the country. In the 1980s, Bhutan launched a campaign to preserve its cultural identity rooted in Tibetan Buddhism, enforcing the ‚ÄúOne Nation, One People‚Äù policy. This included mandatory Tibetan dress codes, language, and customs, which marginalized the Lhotshampa, an ethnic Nepali minority living in southern Bhutan for generations.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Accused of being illegal immigrants and alleged threats to national unity, over 100,000 Lhotshampas were stripped of citizenship and forced to flee, primarily to refugee camps in eastern Nepal. Many lived in limbo for decades, denied fundamental rights in both Bhutan and Nepal.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
